title: Anycubic Prusa i3 | E3D v6 Direct Mount

description.text:
This is a mount for an E3D v6 hotend designed for use on an Anycubic Prusa i3.

The Anycubic Prusa i3 has the same X-carriage dimensions as the Original Prusa i3, so you have many choices of E3D mounts available on Thingiverse. However I wanted this to be a minimal upgrade, and to use the stock extruder. Other than stock parts and the E3D hotend, you just need a few screws and nuts, so no waiting a month for parts to arrive from China before you can upgrade!

This should be compatible with any fan duct designed for the Anet A8, and optionally supports an inductive probe for automatic bed levelling!

Printer:

Anycubic Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

This will get hot, so to prevent warping you should print it with PETG or ABS.

Core parts:

  • E3D v6 or clone kit (direct/bowden/universal doesn't matter as they are all the same)
  • Small length of PTFE tubing (the bowden version of the kit usually comes with this)
  • 2x M3x16mm screws
  • 2x M3x10mm screws
  • 2x M3 nuts (square or hex)

For optional bed level probe:

  • 12mm bed level probe (I use a LJ12A3-4-Z/BY inductive probe)
  • 2x M3x14mm bolts
  • 2x M3 nuts (square or hex)

1. Dissasemble the stock mount, you can do it without removing the x-carriage from the printer. Leave the linear bearings, as we'll be using those!

  2. Check the diameters of holes, they should be tight, but may be too tight. If so, I'd recommend using a round file to make them the correct diameter. Check the fit of all screws before assembly.

  3. Push the heat sink into the mount (it'll be a tight fit), then press on the cover, and screw in the 2x M3x16mm screws. They'll be tight, make sure to do it slowly by hand so they don't produce too much heat.

  4. Mount the assembly onto the linear bearings of the X-carriage using the M4 screws. Loosely fit the screws until they are all in place, then tighten them (but not too tight).

  5. Cut the PTFE tubing to length. The version in the picture is 55mm, the tounge shape at the top is to constrain the filament path better when using flexible filaments. If you don't want to print with flexible filaments you can make it a bit shorter.

  6. Insert the PTFE tubing through the hole, into the heat sink. Screw on the heat break, and make sure the tube is fully pushed down into it. Note that the E3D v6 guide recommends you use thermal paste when attaching the heat break.

  7. Start to screw in the stock M4 screw for mounting the extruder, then place the extruder over that and the PTFE tubing, and tighten. Note that you will still be able to move the extruder slightly even when it's fully tightened, so don't over tighten it.

  8. Attach the X endstop using the stock M2 screws (the nuts aren't needed).

  9. Attach the cooling fan onto the mount using the stock M3x20mm screws, then use 2x M3x10mm screws and 2x M3 nuts to attach it to the main assembly.

  10. If you haven't already, attach the heat block to the heat break. See the E3D documentation for fitting it properly.

  11. Optionally, screw the bed level probe into it's mount, then use 2x M3x14mm screws and 2x M3 nuts to attach it to the main assembly.

  12. Connect up all the wires, you can use a cable tie at the back of the assembly to keep them in place (see picture). Then set the fan at 100% and run PID tuning.

• The screw lengths don't need to be exact, so if you only have slightly longer or shorter it should work fine.

  • The heat sink fan that came with my kit had wires that were too short, so I needed to extend the wires. You do need the heat sink fan for this hotend, so don't skip this if you have the same issue.

  • You will also need a fun duct, it should work with any duct designed for the Anet A8. In the pictures I'm using the Mistral 2.1a.

  • For people with other printers, this may work with you, but you will need to check the dimensions of your extruder - it is not the same as an 'MK8 extruder' found on the Anet A8.

description.text: I designed this to help me push pins out of the e-track when I rearrange the cabinets

This is a Fibonacci striped watch band for sporting your watch with mathematical style! It fits watches that have a 22mm lug width, and a lug to lug distance of 46.2mm (I designed it to fit a Seiko SNDA65 watch). It fits a wrist size of up to ~180mm I took the same watch band design and made it striped! The number of layers in each stripe corresponds with the fibonacci sequence (1-1-2-3-5-8-13... and so on) My blog post about the design: http://colin-ho.com/3d-printed-fibonacci-watch-band/

Makerbot Replicator Settings:
Default slicing settings, infill of 100% and 1 (or 2) shells. Follow these instructions to do the dualstrusion gcode generation in ReplicatorG: http://www.makerbot.com/docs/replicator/dualstrusion/ Printing this is a bit touchy, since using rafts with the current dualstrusion printing procedure "doesn't work well". Thus keep your eyes out for curling! Took me about 4 tries to get this one to print. Post print assembly:

  • After printing is done, take a small file and carefully smooth out the male and female sides of the watch band clasp until they slide and mate snugly (tight enough to no fall out, loose enough to easily take off)

  • Take a thin metal rod (like a small allen key) and insert it through the spring-bar holes to make sure that the spring bars have no obstructions.

  • Attach the watch one spring bar at a time!

  • Enjoy the awesomeness of having a 3D printed watch band!

remixed_from.title: Parametric pulley - lots of tooth profiles

description.text:
Open this design up in Customizer to get started!

I needed a belt to go along with droftarts's fantastic parametric pulley design, so I modified his code to do that. This should of course be printed with flexible filament (such as TPU or NinjaFlex). Surprisingly the belt seems to hold up pretty well in a lot of situations. I've printed it in TPU and used it to drive an electric longboard relatively well (not sure yet how long it will last though).

Tooth profiles currently supported are:
profile == 1 for MXL
profile == 2 for 40 D.P.
profile == 3 for XL
profile == 4 for L
profile == 5 for T2.5
profile == 6 for T5
profile == 7 for T10
profile == 8 for AT5
profile == 9 for HTD 3mm
profile == 10 for HTD 5mm
profile == 11 for HTD 8mm
profile == 12 for GT2 2mm
profile == 13 for GT2 3mm
profile == 14 for GT2 5mm

Open this design in either Customizer or OpenSCAD. Input the number of teeth, which gear profile to use (profiles are listed above in the description), the thickness of the belt, and it's width. Then generate your object, download, then print it with 100% infill with flexible filament (I've only tested it with TPU so far, which seems to work decently well).

comments.text: Hey, this is really cool, I'm just wondering how far have you gotten with your TPU printed belt? I'm thinking of just printing belts instead of buying them. prices add up fast.
comments.author: aleksvan23

comments.text:
I would still invest in a regular belt, you can find them pretty cheap usually. I only whipped this together because I wasn't very patient waiting for my belt to ship. While it did work better than expected, there's still a few noticible downsides that would prevent me at least from using it in anything but prototyping:
Using it for those few days showed a few things:
First of all, the belt lasted much longer than I expected. Even after a lot of use, the TPU didn't seem to wear down at all like I would imagine it to. However, it turned out there another problem. TPU (or at least the kind I have) seems to have a bit of "slickness" to it, similar to nylon. This wasn't ideal, because I noticed the belt would skip teeth more often under heavy loads because of the slickness. This could probably be countered by either using a different flexible material that's a little more "dry" like rubber, or you could just add a few less teeth onto the belt to keep it tighter around the pulleys. This is probably necessary anyway since the TPU does have a bit of stretch to it.

title: Handy Pasta Strainer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A handy strainer for pouring out the water after cooking pasta or vegetables. Easy to just rinse after use, keep on a hook near the kitchen sink.

It's made to fit smallish pots, up to around a diameter or 187 mm. Total length of the model is 273 mm, so it won't fit very small heatbeds. Fits the prusa mk2s heatbed (25x21cm) when rotated diagonally.

This must be printed with a material that can take heat. I used PC (polycarbonate) for this, other alternatives could be ColorFabb HT, or some of the high-temp PLA filaments that can be annealed in the oven after printing. ABS should work as well, but that might not be food safe. 100% infill is also important for hygienic reasons.

When slicing, think about the orientation of the longer handle, mirror the model if you would rather have it on the other side.

I've included two versions as I noticed the polycarbonate filament I used is a bit more flexible than I'd imagined, and the strainer came out a bit more bendy than I would have liked. So I added more strength to the handle and uploaded a second version, you can use that if you print with a slightly flexible filament.

Please post a Make if you make this!

remixed_from.title: Auger-based feeder for animals, fish etc using Nema 17 stepper motor

description.text:
This started as a remix to make the auger more printable by splitting it axially. The original auger is difficult because of the constant overhang and printing with support is a huge PITA.

The split model prints each side flat and is glued together afterwards (you'll need to flip the halves down on their long sides before printing). This also makes the shaft much stronger. It doesn't take much glue (superglue or epoxy) to join - the joint at the base is most important. I didn't bother gluing each of the screw "threads". A ring is then glued around the base to strengthen the glue joint against the force of the set screw (opening centered on the setscrew hole).

I progressed to remodeling the trough as I didn't want to use melt-in inserts. The motorplate fasteners are now a 5mm bolt and plain nut. I also much reduced the printing time and filament usage by reducing the solid volumes. It's in two pieces, mostly so I could check the bottom half for fit before sinking hours of print time into it.

Dec 18 Rev:
In getting this working I made some changes to the files. Mostly they serve to prevent or at least minimize pieces of cat food getting caught in the works and stopping the motor.
However, it is very difficult to prevent that completely, so I have the motor go forward approx 45 degrees and then reverse for 10, and repeat as needed. When a piece of food gets caught and stalls the stepper, the reversal serves to dislodge it.

The slanted plate is glued in place after other assembly and is to prevent a lot of food dumping out the end sporadically. The amount dispensed was very uneven when the end of the auger was exposed. Now I can dispense 33 grams (about 1/4 cup) within a gram or two using four full auger rotations. (I'm sure the plate could be modeled into the other bits but the hardware was progressively modified as it came together, so there you go.)

For control I used a Raspberry Pi, Pi Touchscreen and Adafruit Stepper motor hat. The stepper I got off of Amazon. The combination of Adafruit hat and not particularly strong stepper turned out to be perfect. The stepper stalls when a piece of food is caught rather than breaking the auger or trough.

title: Samsung Nexus/Galaxy phone holder with cover and exterior antenna..

description.text: I wanted a holder that I didn't have to peel the silicon cover off the phone all the time to use. The aftermarket clamp types were chunky and ugly. I also wanted to charge the phone without manually plugging in a cable.

The holder is made to accept a Samsung Nexus or Galaxy2 with the soft silicon sleeves that are available for them. Once printed, you have the option of purchasing a micro USB car charging cable for it. Insert the micro USB cable through the square hole at the base and slide the phone down to meet it and then push the phone all the way till it seats. Carefully then spot some super glue around the micro USB plug and the square hole to locate it in the correct position. Once dry, carefully withdraw the phone. You can now add more glue or carefully fill any void with silastic or aradite or something that locates the plug permanently. Sliding the phone in should now line it up to meet the micro USB plug every time. The four holes on the flat back of the holder are for a cheap Samsung car holder I purchased off eBay. It has a suction cup for the windsceen, or alternatively a vent mount. They are about $14. The part that meets my phone holder is a rectangle with four tangs that fit into the back of my holder, and pushed sideways to lock in very positively.
The larger recess and thin channel in the back are for a antenna coil I also found on eBay. Its postioned up against the back of the phone and allows it to use an exterior car antenna. title: Split 1x3x4 (Polished)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I was not super happy with original RyanPuzzle's design because it was:

  • too loose (huge tolerance)
  • too catchy (sharp corners)
  • consist of pieces of 2 differen things with different scale (unclear how to print)
  • Screw mechanism is not well designed

All credits still go to RyanPuzzle, consider this thing as just a polished version of his puzzle.

In this design I used 20mm blocks (vs 19mm in the original Rubik's Cube) - this is just for easier measurement. I added fillets to all edges, so all pieces do not catch each other on movements. 0.2mm tolerance works fine in my case.

One more note on the design. All pieces are bulging and can can't be printed as is without supports. First of all I do not like printing with supports, so I just split each piece into body and cap and then glued together. I printed my puzzle in ABS and used acethone as a glue. Moreover my printer swallows first few layers (smear it on the table), so I added 0.2mm height to each part. After gluing and sanding all pieces became exactly 20x20x20mm.

If you feel this approach is overcomplicated - you may use non-split version of puzzle pieces. See parts with 'As Is' in file name. Note, they are not properly rotated and not prepared for printing. Use you favorite slicer and printing approach.

Here is the design source
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/93b131d120f9af7d02b9e46a/v/a7214498a2ca6e0f408f1f03/e/544aa32c5e8e7b70ff0e0f93
Feel free to fork and adjust if needed. All main parameters are extracted to dedicated variables on at the top of feature list.

Feel free to ask me any questions regarding to this puzzle.

Printer:

Graber i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm layer, 0.3, nozzle

Infill:

25%

Notes:

No specific slicer settings needed.

Printing

Print top and bottom of each part

  • Edge pieces consist of 2 identical parts
  • Corners and small edges consist of a body and a small cap
  • Each center piece consist of 2 symmetrical bodies and caps for them (4 pieces for each center piece)

Number of parts to print is in the file name

Glue and sand

Glue pieces of each part. I used acethone for parts printed in ABS and dychroethan (TOXIC!!!!) or CA for PLA. Then sand each piece to remove roughness on the seal.

I used 150 grit sand paper to remove roughness, and 320 + 500 grit for making sides flat and smooth.

Control size of each cube - they must be 20x20x20 (or 20x20x40 for edge and centers). If you sand too much puzzle may be loose.

Due to printing mistakes and poor quality plastic some of corners wrapped up. After gluing parts I got small gaps, that I filled with milliput (analogue)

Paint

I used acrylic paint bought at automotive shop.

Have to admit that non-painted puzzle turns much better. Perhaps I need to search for some other paint.

Screws

As a screw I used 75mm piece of a M3 thread rod (bought at local DIY store).

On one side I put a M3 locknut with a drip of CA to avoid it unscrew. This side goes to Edge 2 (one that has hex-shaped hole)

After assembling the puzzle arount thread rod:

  • add a spring - I got one as Rubik's Cube core and springs kit ($1-2 on ebay). Actually this is optional as I do not see any necessity for puzzle tentioning.
  • screw a nut. I used a M3 nut head for my screw driver (see picture)
Stickers

I cut stickers manually with vynil film bought in local decoration shop.

Though next time I would prefer cutting stickers using a plotter. I uploaded stickers drawings

Lubricate

Use silicone lubricant spray

description.text:
Recently, I had designed some parts that used some large printed threads. Despite having added clearance between the internal and external threads, I couldn't screw them together, even after considerable sanding. I discovered LuckyPant's Dimensional Calibrationa Tool https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1982686 which offered insight into radial compensation.
His design is great, but I wasn't able to use it due to limitations of my printer, calipers and a desire to have a model that prints quickly and doesn't use much filament.
To use this test print, you will need to have calipers or a micrometer.
After printing the test piece, make a series of measurements and enter the values into the spreadsheet. It will supply correction values for scaling and horizontal calibration. I've added some notes on how to do this with Simplify3D, but I believe similar factors will be in other slicers.
The correction values that it calculated may be small, but they have made a huge difference for me.
Although they aren't part of the calibration process, I've also added a series of small holes that can be tested with drill bits to see how small of a hole that I could produce accurately.
